 used in the same manner to neutralize the effect of heparin given before surgery and during extracorporeal circulation procedures like those performed in hemodialysis or cardiac surgery [F3559, F3562, L5371, L5443]. ', 'When not complexed with heparin, protamine sulfate by itself demonstrates a weak anticoagulant effect and also evidently prolongs the euglycaemic phase of the human body when used as an excipient in certain injectable insulin formulations [F3562]. Furthermore, some animal studies have suggested that the long-term oral administration of protamine sulfate may favourably decrease serum lipid concentrations, presumably by enhancing the actions of the carnitine palmitoyltransferase-2 and acyl-CoA oxidase enzymes [F3562]. Related studies have also shown that protamine sulfate may be able to decrease intestinal fat absorption and might possess certain antibacterial effects [F3562].



Additionally, studies have also determined that protamine sulfate elicits effects on the clotting factors human factor Xa and human antithrombin (AT) [F3562]. In particular, it has been shown that protamine sulfate is capable of transforming and degrading factor Xa to inactive moieties, transforming Xa-AT complexes, promoting the digestive degradation of primary Xa-AT complexes to tertiary complexes, and ultimately promotes a reduction in total complex formulation via the hydrolysis of factor Xa moieties [F3562].', 'DrugBank', 0, 0, 0);
